    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1980-10-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1980-10-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="226"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d226">
                <head>226. Memorandum From Secretary of Defense <persName corresp="#p_BH_2"
                        >Brown</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1"
                        >Carter</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d226fn1">Source: Carter Library, National
                        Security Affairs, <persName corresp="#p_BZK_1">Brzezinski</persName>
                        Material, General Odom File, Box 28, Middle East Command Post: 4–10/80.
                        Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1980-10-22">October 22, 1980</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Command Relationships in Saudi Arabia (U)</item>
                </list>
                <p>(S) This memorandum responds to your request for an outline of the current
                    command structure and communication routing between <gloss target="#t_AWACS_1"
                        >AWACS</gloss> over Saudi Arabia and our military forces in the Middle
                    East-Persian Gulf region.<note n="2" xml:id="d226fn2">Not found.</note> These
                    are outlined in detail at Tabs A and B, respectively.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d226fn3">Attached but not printed are two routing charts entitled
                        “Command Relationships (Saudi Arabia/Adjacent Waters)” and “Comm/Data
                        Flow.”</note>
                </p>
                <p>(S) <hi rend="italic">Command Structure</hi>. In essence, our current command
                    relationships are those provided in the Unified Command Plan. Operational
                    control of the deployed <gloss target="#t_AWACS_1">AWACS</gloss> and associated
                    ground radar and support units in Saudi Arabia is exercised through <gloss
                        target="#t_CINCEUR_1">CINCEUR</gloss> by his <gloss target="#t_USAF_1"
                        >USAF</gloss> component commander’s representative in Saudi Arabia
                    (ELF–ONE). Operational control of naval forces in both the Persian Gulf and the
                    Arabian Sea is passed from <gloss target="#t_CINCPAC_1">CINCPAC</gloss> through
                        <gloss target="#t_COMSEVENTHFLT_1">COMSEVENTHFLT</gloss> to Commander Task
                    Force 70 (<gloss target="#t_CTF_1">CTF</gloss>–70). For the air defense mission,
                        <gloss target="#t_CINCEUR_1">CINCEUR</gloss> has been designated the
                    supported commander, with <gloss target="#t_CINCPAC_1">CINCPAC</gloss>
                    supporting him. Those roles would be reversed in the event of a maritime
                    mission; e.g., mine clearing or active protection of shipping.</p>
                <p>(S) <hi rend="italic">Communication Routing</hi>. Air defense resources currently
                    in the region consist of an integrated air defense net which includes <gloss
                        target="#t_AWACS_1">AWACS</gloss>, Saudi and <gloss target="#t_US_1"
                        >US</gloss> ground radars, Saudi Hawk facilities, Saudi and <gloss
                        target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> Navy fighter aircraft, and a <gloss
                        target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> fleet air defense cruiser deployed within the
                    Gulf. All these units can communicate by voice. Additionally, the <gloss
                        target="#t_AWACS_1">AWACS</gloss> can relay radar data to <gloss
                        target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> ships and aircraft of TF–70, as well as to its
                    own ground processing center, which provides the link to Saudi forces. Direct
                    communications circuits (via satellite) have been established between the
                    National Military Command Center (for the National Command Authorities) and
                    ELF–ONE, <gloss target="#t_AWACS_1">AWACS</gloss>, and TF–70 in the area.</p>
                <p>(S) <hi rend="italic">Summary Evaluation</hi>. Although the current command
                    relationships are naturally more complex than a single-<gloss target="#t_CINC_1"
                        >CINC</gloss> operation, both <pb facs="0769" n="726" xml:id="pg_726"/> the
                        <gloss target="#t_JCS_1">JCS</gloss> and I believe they are working
                    satisfactorily at the current level of operations. Should our involvement in the
                    region become markedly greater, we would consider a gradual transition of
                    responsibility by introducing the Headquarters, Rapid Deployment Joint Task
                    Force (<gloss target="#t_RDJTF_1">RDJTF</gloss>) into the area to command all
                    forces in the region in accordance with the <gloss target="#t_RDJTF_1"
                        >RDJTF</gloss> command relationships approved this summer.<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d226fn4">See <ref target="#d88">Document 88</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BH_2">
                            <hi rend="strong">Harold Brown</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
